caption.text: Map of the results of the 2010 Amber Valley council election. [[LINK|lang_en|Labour_Party_(UK)|Labour]] in red and [[LINK|lang_en|Conservative_Party_(UK)|Conservatives]] in blue. Wards in grey were not contested in 2010.

items.text: The **2010 Amber Valley Borough Council election** took place on 6 May 2010 to elect members of [[LINK|lang_en|Amber_Valley|Amber Valley]] [[LINK|lang_en|Borough_status_in_the_United_Kingdom|Borough]] Council in [[LINK|lang_en|Derbyshire|Derbyshire]], [[LINK|lang_en|England|England]]. One third of the council was up for election and the [[LINK|lang_en|Conservative_Party_(UK)|Conservative party]] stayed in overall control of the council.[[CITE|1|http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/council/html/3650.stm]]
After the election, the composition of the council was
15 seats were contested in the election by a total of 50 candidates.[[CITE|3|/wiki/Derby_Telegraph]]

The Conservatives campaigned on their record of controlling the council for the previous 10 years, pointing to keeping [[LINK|lang_en|Council_tax|council tax]] increases low and plans to [[LINK|lang_en|Urban_renewal|regenerate]] local towns.[[CITE|4|/wiki/Derby_Telegraph]] However [[LINK|lang_en|Labour_Party_(UK)|Labour]] pledged to appoint people as area managers who would be a contact point for people to bring any problems and planned to use [[LINK|lang_en|Compulsory_purchase_order|compulsory purchase orders]] to bring empty properties into use.[[CITE|4|/wiki/Derby_Telegraph]] Meanwhile, the [[LINK|lang_en|Liberal_Democrats_(UK)|Liberal Democrats]] targeted seats in [[LINK|lang_en|Belper|Belper]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Duffield,_Derbyshire|Duffield]] campaigning on regeneration, [[LINK|lang_en|Recycling|recycling]] and litter, while the [[LINK|lang_en|British_National_Party|British National Party]] hoped to increase on the 2 seats they held in [[LINK|lang_en|Heanor|Heanor]].[[CITE|4|/wiki/Derby_Telegraph]]

The results saw no change in the party balance as Labour held the 8 seats they had been defending and the Conservatives the other 7 seats, meaning the Conservatives remained in control of the council.[[CITE|5|/wiki/Derby_Telegraph]] Neither the Liberal Democrats or British National Party won any seats, with the British National Party vote dropping in Heanor where it held 2 seats.[[CITE|5|/wiki/Derby_Telegraph]]
